Technological determinism is a term that covers a wide range of ideas in practice – from the technological impetus or the technological imperative to the strict sense that human destiny is governed by logic associated with scientific laws and their manifestation in technology.
Two common ideas are shared between most interpretations of technological determinism: the very development of technology goes along a path far beyond cultural or political influence or technology itself affects inherent, not socially conditioned societies.
For example, one can say that a motor vehicle necessarily leads to the development of roads.
However, a national road network will not be economically advantageous only for a handful of cars, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the value of owning a car.
The mass ownership of cars also led to the increased frequency of road accidents, which required the invention of new health care techniques to restore damaged bodies.
